.TH _printf 1 "11 november 2022" "1.0" "_printf man page"
.SH NAME
_printf - formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
#include "main.h"
.sp
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The function _printf() produces output according to a format as described below.
The function writes output to stdout, the standard output stream, under the control of a string that specifies how subsequent arguments are converted for output.

This implementation supports the conversion specifiers listed in
.BR "SUPPORTED CONVERSIONS" .
Flag characters, field width, precision, and length modifiers are
.B not
supported; each conversion is a single character after the percent sign (for example
.BR %d ", " %x ", " %% ).

.B Format of the format string
.PP
The format string is composed of ordinary characters (copied as-is) and conversion specifications.
A conversion specification is introduced by
.B %
followed immediately by a single conversion character (for example
.BR %s ", " %u ).
Unknown specifiers are printed literally (for example
.B %p
prints the characters
.B %p
without consuming an argument).

.B SUPPORTED CONVERSIONS
.TP
.BR d ", " i
The
.B int
argument is converted to signed decimal notation.

.TP
.BR c
The
.B int
argument is converted to an
.BR "unsigned char" ,
and the resulting character is written.

.TP
.BR s
The
.B "const char *"
argument is expected to be a pointer to a string. Characters are written up to (but not including) the terminating null byte
.RB ( \(aq\\0\(aq ).
If the pointer is NULL,
.B "(null)"
is printed instead.

.TP
.B %
A literal percent character is written. This conversion does not consume an argument.

.TP
.BR b
The
.B "unsigned int"
argument is converted to binary (base 2).

.TP
.BR u
The
.B "unsigned int"
argument is converted to unsigned decimal notation.

.TP
.BR o
The
.B "unsigned int"
argument is converted to unsigned octal notation.

.TP
.BR x
The
.B "unsigned int"
argument is converted to unsigned hexadecimal notation using lowercase letters
.B abcdef .

.TP
.BR X
The
.B "unsigned int"
argument is converted to unsigned hexadecimal notation using uppercase letters
.BR ABCDEF .

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful return, these functions return the number of
characters printed (excluding the null byte used to end output to
strings).
If an output error is encountered, a negative value is returned.

.SH EXAMPLES
To print integer:
.RS 
.nf
#include "main.h"
_printf("Numbers of apples: %d", 10);
.RE

To print strings or character:
.RS
.nf
#include "main.h"
_printf("Name of the school: %s", "Holberton");
_printf("First letter of Orange: %c", 'O');
.RE

To convert in binary:
.RS
.nf
#include "main.h"
_printf("binary of 98: %b", 98);
.RE

Unsigned decimal, octal, and hexadecimal:
.RS
.nf
#include "main.h"
_printf("u=%u o=%o x=%x X=%X\\n", 255u, 255u, 255u, 255u);
.RE

